(* sitemap.ebnf — the Sitemaps 0.9 protocol as a schema grammar over the XML
   element vocabulary (https://www.sitemaps.org/protocol.html, and as consumed
   by Google Search: https://developers.google.com/search/docs/crawling-indexing/sitemaps/build-sitemap).

   Like xmile's rss-2.0.ebnf, this is NOT a character grammar: xmile's
   lang/xml.ebnf already parses the bytes into the generic Tag tree. This
   grammar describes the sitemap *vocabulary* — which elements nest in which —
   so the projector (service/sitemap.go, riding xmile's generic engine) can
   restructure a parsed Tag tree into a typed AST. It is the EBNF analogue of a
   DTD/XSD, compiled to a proto descriptor by gluon's compiler through xmile's
   service.CompileGrammar (the EBNF_VOCAB front-end).

   Conventions (interpreted by service.CompileGrammar):

     - A rule is an element; its body lists the child elements it may contain.
     - `text` is the character content of a leaf element; it has no rule of its
       own and lowers to a `string text` field.
     - Any reference with no rule of its own becomes a string field; every other
       reference becomes a message field. (Same rule CompileDTD uses.)

   TWO roots, one vocabulary. A sitemap file is either a <urlset> (a set of
   URLs) or a <sitemapindex> (a set of child sitemaps). gluon's GrammarToAST
   emits a message for every rule, and xmile's Process resolves the document
   root by element name, so one compiled descriptor serves both roots. `urlset`
   is written first only to satisfy the "start rule is first" convention; both
   are top-level roots.

   Order-insensitive by design. The spec lists a fixed child order
   (loc, lastmod, changefreq, priority), but real-world sitemaps routinely
   reorder or repeat, so — exactly as rss-2.0.ebnf models <channel> — each
   container is a repetition of a choice ({ a | b | ... }), which lowers to a
   repeated message-with-oneof that preserves document order across variants.

   What is NOT here (a CFG cannot express it; enforced in service/validate.go):
     - the root's namespace (http://www.sitemaps.org/schemas/sitemap/0.9);
     - <loc> is required and <= 2048 characters, and must be a URL;
     - <lastmod> is a W3C Datetime;
     - <changefreq> is one of always|hourly|daily|weekly|monthly|yearly|never;
     - <priority> is a number in [0.0, 1.0] (default 0.5);
     - a file has at most 50,000 entries and is at most 50 MiB uncompressed.

   Namespace extensibility (Google's image:, video:, news:, and xhtml:link
   alternates ride a sitemap in their own namespaces) is enforced by the
   projector, not the grammar: a namespace-qualified element/attribute is a
   tolerated extension, an unprefixed unknown one is invalid — the same rule
   RSS 2.0 uses. *)

urlset = { url } ;

url = { loc | lastmod | changefreq | priority } ;

sitemapindex = { sitemap } ;

sitemap = { loc | lastmod } ;

loc        = text ;
lastmod    = text ;
changefreq = text ;
priority   = text ;
